1969 CHATEAU BOTTLED

Because of half a normal production, the opening prices of the 1969 was record breaking. They are still in barrel and are showing well. The better Chateau bottlings should reach our cellars between the Fall of 1971 and the Spring of 1972. We will keep you advised as to their progress and will offer them after their arrival. They are worth waiting for.

1968 CHATEAU BOTTLED

Certainly, the ’68s are better than the ’63s or ’65s. The great vineyards, through selection and reduction of total quantity have been able to provide excellent wines, equalling the 1960s. They are starting to arrive but we do think they re- quire a few more months of bottle age. We will offer them during the Fall-Winter of 1971. The prices will be relatively modest and they will be ready for drinking.

1967 CHATEAU BOTTLED

Exceptionally fine, soft, fruity, quick maturing—but likely to have its excellence overlooked since it never shared in the publicity drum- beating that was showered on both 1966 and 1969.

1965 CHATEAU BOTTLED

The rule here must be selection. Entirely delightful wines were produced at some chateaux, whereas others produced light and inconsequential wines. Based on our tastings, we single out below two examples that will provide eminent drinking pleasure at relatively modest cost.

CHATEAU PICHON LALANDE ....... 2.49 30.15 We do not know what they did at this Pauillac vineyard to make their 1965 so delightful—but we feel we would be re- miss if we did not bring this one to your attention.

CHATEAU HAUT BRION ..... 4.89 52.80 This First Growth Graves commands over $60 the case, wholesale, in Bordeaux. The nobility of the soil, the care and selection, the dedication—all are reflected here in the elegance, balance, bouquet and satisfying taste. True, this is not a wine for laying down—but if you want to experience the kind of grace that a Chateau Haut Brion can bestow— and you are selecting wines to be consumed during the next two or three years, to be served proudly at even the most distinguished of dinner parties—we do not think you should overlook Chateau Haut Brion 1965.
